entry:
*Felis margarita* is one of the most specialized felines. The specialization for desert life is seen in the general structure of the skull, its facial and cranial proportions, the position of the orbits, and especially in the maximal development of the auditory apparatus. This species has an extremely broad, flat face with large, triangular ear pinnae set low on the head and lacking an apical tuft.

The following entry is a summary of the article found at [https://doi.org/10.1093/mspecies/sev007](https://academic.oup.com/mspecies/article/47/924/63/2609388/Felis-margarita-Carnivora-Felidae?searchresult=1). Additional images, appendices, and details can be found there.

## Description

*Felis margarita* has a stocky build with a tail that is about one-half the head and body length. In addition to ears set low on the head, *F. margarita* has relatively short legs giving this cat a low profile, a possible advantage in its sparsely vegetated desert environment. The claws on the forelimbs are short, sharply curved, and highly compressed laterally. The claws on the hind limbs are less compressed, weakly curved, more elongate, and relatively blunt. The retractile apparatus of the claws is poorly developed.

The crown of the head is pale sandy with poorly defined striations. The upper and lower lips and chin are white, and throat has a faint buffy wash. A faint reddish line runs from the outside corner of each eye down across the cheek. The greenish yellow eyes are large and surrounded by a white ring. The rhinarium is black; the vibrissae are white and up to 8cm long. The backs of the ears are tawny brown at the base and black at the tip and the ears are directed outward from the crown. The inner ears are protected from blowing sand by a dense growth of long white hairs that spans the ear opening and continues along the ear margins to the apex.

The pelage is typically pale sandy to straw gray in color, with the dorsum slightly darker than the venter (Sausman 1997b). The dorsum is usually without spots or stripes, but some individuals have a finely speckled pelage with black over the shoulders and silvery gray on the upper flanks. The venter is white. Two to 3 prominent black bands ring the forelegs. The last one-third of the tail has a varying number of black rings and the tail ends with a black tip. The thighs are marked with black barring and the flanks with 7–8 indistinct reddish-brown vertical stripes, broken into spots with black in places. The palms and soles of the feet are covered with dense, long (15–30mm), black fur that protects them from the hot desert substrate and assists in movement through loose sand. This characteristic makes the tracks of *F. margarita* indistinct and difficult to detect.

In addition to being restricted to sandy and rocky desert habitat, *F. margarita* is distinguished from other potentially co-occurring small felids (F. chaus—jungle cat and F. silvestris—wildcat) by its pale pelage; prominent facial and foreleg markings; large, broad, and low set ears that lack tufts; rounded cranium and shortened rostrum; and relatively broad paws that are covered with hair.

## General Characters

The *Felis margarita* adult has soft, dense fur, which protects it from the cold nighttime desert temperatures. There is no sexual dimorphism in pelage coloration, but there are marked age-related color differences. The pelage color of newborn *F. margarita* is pale yellow or chestnut-gray speckled with small brown, indistinct spots on the back and especially the flanks. A dark but indistinct band runs along the spine. The head has several dark longitudinal stripes, which widen at the neck. The tail has a black tip with 2 rings anterior to it and 3 or 4 dark spots along the dorsal surface. After the 1st molt, young grow pelage that is similar to adults, but darker on the dorsum along the spine and with small dark spots behind the shoulders. Banding on the legs and markings on the tail are more distinct than for newborns.

The *F. margarita* skull most closely resembles that of Pallas’s cat. The cranium is broad, the rostrum short, and the zygomatic arches wide. The anterior ends of zygomatic processes gradually taper in. The eye sockets are large, more spherical, and more forward directed than in F. silvestris. The tympanic bullae are more inflated than in other Old World cats. The skulls of both sexes are similarly proportioned, but the female skull is about 85% of the size of the male skull.

## Distribution

*Felis margarita* is found in sand and stony desert environments in a wide but disjunct distribution through the deserts of northern Africa, the Arabian Peninsula, and southwest and central Asia. The lack of *F. margarita* records in apparently suitable areas may reflect inadequate study rather than species absence. Consequently, distribution maps must be interpreted with caution.


## Ontogeny and Reproduction

### Ontogeny

*Felis margarita* young are born helpless, blind, and with their ear passages closed, but covered with fur. The body measurements (mm) of a newborn were: head and body length 143; tail length 58; hind foot length 32; and ear length 9. Birth mass of 2 newborns was 39g and 50g. The mean mass of 4 stillborn *F. margarita* young was 72g (range 70–75g) and the mean mass of 4 living newborns was 71g (range 56–84g). A male 2–3 days old weighed 108g and a female of the same age weighed 105g. Young grow rapidly gaining roughly 12g/day during the first 3 weeks of postnatal life; their eyes open at 11–14 days (range 12–16 days). *F. margarita* young begin walking at 21 days (range 20–22 days) and eat solid food at 5 weeks.

*Felis margarita* young could become independent as early as 4 months but normally are relatively independent by about 6–8 months of age. *F. margarita* young reach three-quarters of adult size by 5 months.

In central Asia, adult males weighed 3,350–3,500g. Weights of wild *F. margarita* adults from Turkmenistan varied from 2,100 to 3,400g for males (n = 12) and 1,400 to 3,100g for females (n = 5). The mean weight of 4 males from Pakistan was 2,780g (range 1,350–3,100g). Two adult males from the Sinai weighed 2,139 and 2,674g.

### Reproduction

In captivity, *Felis margarita* is not a seasonal breeder and may breed more than once per year. In wild *F. margarita*, the reproductive season depends upon location, but the potential for 2 litters per year exists. Births are reported from January to April in the Sahara. Young *F. margarita* have been found in March and April and a 6-week-old litter was found in October in Balochistan, Pakistan. *F. margarita* litters from this area typically have either 2 or 3 young. In Turkmenistan, births occur during April and nursing-young have been taken from burrows in late April and May. In many areas where *F. margarita* occurs, the best vegetation growth is in March and April, and many rodents breed during this time providing an abundant food resource. Differences in climate or resource availability influence breeding season length.

## Ecology

*Felis margarita* is not well studied because this species lives in a harsh environment that is often remote, and these cats are nocturnal, subterranean, and secretive animals. *F. margarita* occurs at low densities in disjunct populations throughout its range. No ecological explanation for the gaps in *F. margarita* distribution has been proposed despite seemly appropriate habitat.

*Felis margarita* is the only cat to occur exclusively in deserts, inhabiting vegetated sand desert, sand dune plains, sand and gravel desert, and rocky desert habitats. This species is more common in sandy desert and less common where the substrate is compacted or composed of clay. The distribution and abundance of rodent prey influences where *F. margarita* occurs. Its small-mammal prey often live clustered around vegetation and generally do not extend onto bare sand, especially during drought years.

*Felis margarita* inhabits an environment that experiences dramatic temperature variation. Daytime surface temperatures may approach 124°C and the air temperature can range up to 58°C in the shade, but night air temperatures are much lower, ranging down to −0.5°C. Air temperature during the day in the Karakum Desert can exceed 40°C in the summer; temperature on the desert surface can exceed 80°C. It snows in the winter when temperatures may drop as low as −25°C
